#+TAGS: kernel anal


* modprobe							:kernel:anal:
* Description
* Usage
** View all loaded modules
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
less /proc/modules
#+END_SRC
or
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
lsmod
#+END_SRC 

** Add a module
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
modprobe vfat
#+END_SRC
this will install any dependent modules

** Remove a module
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
modprobe -r vfat
#+END_SRC
this will remove the selected module and deals with dependencies

** Get information on a module
#+BEGIN_SRC sh
modinfo ehci_pci
#+END_SRC
this will show all kernel parameters available near the bottom of the output

** Set kernel parameter
/lib/modprobe.d/ - shouldn't usually modify these files
/etc/modprobe.d/ - here is where modificattions should be made
man 5 modprobe.d - this explains conf of modprobe directory

- changing cdrom lockdoor parameter
1. create a file in /etc/modprobe.d with the following
cdrom.conf
#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
options cdrom lockdoor=0
#+END_EXAMPLE
this will mean that the parameter is now set to 0

